<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-154-404  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 154 404.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Feb 7 1990 n1359* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM Italia turns in 1989 domestic business up 10%, exports tosiblings up 16%.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   IBM Italia S.p.A. (earnings).andO;Product:   IBM AS-400 (Minicomputer) (sales statistics).andO;Topic:     Review of Past YearSalesProfit MarginExport.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM ITALIA TURNS IN 1989 DOMESTIC BUSINESS UP 10%,andM;EXPORTS TO SIBLINGS UP 16%andM;IBM Italia SpA has followed its French and West German siblings in bringingout its 1989 figures, and coupled with the numbers from the other twoEuropean majors to have reported, they suggest that IBM UK had a pretty dimyear within the UK market, although - as with the Italians, and in contrastto France and Germany, exports likely did rather better than the domesticmarket.andP;  IBM Italia reported turnover up 12.6% to the equivalent of $5,800m,and within that figure, domestic business grew 10.4% to $3,370m, whileexports to other IBM Europe companies soared 15.8% to $2,429m.andP;  Why didexports climb so much? Italy makes the AS/400 for Europe, and lusty AS/400sales no doubt contributed to the good business done in their home markets byFrance and Germany (CI No 1,351).andP;  The poor export performance by France -3090s, and Germany - big disks, implies that IBM UK had a rotten year in the3090 market in 1989.IBM Italia hasn't worked out profits yet, but reckonsthat they are likely to be up on last year's $451m, despite net marginsfalling to about 8% from the 8.8% the Italian company recorded last year.andO;</TEXT></DOC>